\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 Prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 has an element whose order is the least common multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Soln.

\series default
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 be the elements of orders 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m=\prod_{i=1}^{k}p_{i}^{m_{i}},\qquad n=\prod_{i=1}^{k}p_{i}^{n_{i}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

s are prime divisors of 
\begin_inset Formula $mn$
\end_inset

.
 Denote 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\{i\,\colon\, m_{i}\ge n_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N=\{i\,\colon\, m_{i}<n_{i}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m'=\prod_{i\in M}p_{i},\qquad n'=\prod_{i\in N}p_{i},
\]

\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{lcm}(m,n)=m'n',\qquad\gcd(m',n')=1.
\]

\end_inset

 Also note that 
\begin_inset Formula $a'=a^{m/m'}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b'=b^{n/n'}$
\end_inset

 are elements of orders 
\begin_inset Formula $m'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n'$
\end_inset

, respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $a'b'$
\end_inset

 is of order 
\begin_inset Formula $m'n'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $(a'b')^{m'n'}=a^{mn'}b^{nm'}=e$
\end_inset

.
 Now suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(a'b')^{k}=e$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $a'^{k}=b'^{-k}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $a'^{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b'^{k}$
\end_inset

 have the same orders.
 We know that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
o(a'^{k})=\frac{m'}{\gcd(m',k)},\qquad o(b'^{k})=\frac{n'}{\gcd(n',k)}.
\]

\end_inset

 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{m'}{\gcd(m',k)}=\frac{n}{\gcd(n',k)}
\]

\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $m'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n'$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime, both sides must be equal to 1.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\gcd(m',k)=m'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gcd(n',k)=n'$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $m'n'$
\end_inset

, which implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $k\ge m'n'$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $m'n'$
\end_inset

 is indeed the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $a'b'$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore we have proved that there is an element of order 
\begin_inset Formula $m'n'=\text{lcm}(m,n)$
\end_inset

, so our proof is finished.
\end_layout

