\begin_layout Theorem
All groups of order 9 are abelian.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Brute force.

\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be of group of order 9.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 has an element of order 9 it is clearly abelian.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Suppose no element has order 9.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq e$
\end_inset

 be an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Then it has order 3 so 
\begin_inset Formula $e,a,a^{2}$
\end_inset

 are distinct.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 be another element different from these 3.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 also has order 3.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{2}\neq a$
\end_inset

 for otherwise 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{4}=b=a^{2}.$
\end_inset

 Likewise 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{2}\neq a^{2}$
\end_inset

 because otherwise 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{4}=b=a^{4}=a$
\end_inset

.
 So now we have 5 distinct elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 viz., 
\begin_inset Formula $e,a,b,a^{2},b^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We show that 
\begin_inset Formula $ab,ab^{2},ba^{2},a^{2}b^{2}$
\end_inset

are the other 4 distinct element.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ab=e\ \implies b=a^{2},\quad ab=a\ \implies b=e,\quad ab=b\ \implies a=e
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ab=a^{2}\ \implies b=a,\quad ab=b^{2}\ \implies a=b
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ab^{2}=e\ \implies ab^{3}=b\ \implies a=b,\quad ab^{2}=a\ \implies b^{2}=e
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ab^{2}=b\ \implies ab=e,\quad ab^{2}=a^{2}\ \implies b^{2}=a,\quad ab^{2}=b^{2}\ \implies a=e
\]

\end_inset

Similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $ba^{2}$
\end_inset

 is distinct from 
\begin_inset Formula $e,a,b,a^{2},b^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Finally
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a^{2}b^{2}=e\ \implies b^{2}=a\quad a^{2}b^{2}=a\ \implies a^{2}=b^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a^{2}b^{2}=b\ \implies a^{2}=b^{2}\quad a^{2}b^{2}=a^{2}\ \implies b^{2}=e
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a^{2}b^{2}=b^{2}\ \implies a^{2}=e.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
These elements are also distinct from one another.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ab=ab^{2}\ \implies b=e,\quad ab=a^{2}b^{2}\ \implies ab=e
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ab=ba^{2}\ \implies aba=b
\]

\end_inset

but 
\begin_inset Formula $bababa=e$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $bbba=e\ \implies a=e$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ab^{2}=a^{2}b^{2}\ \implies a=e
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ab^{2}=ba^{2}\ \implies a=ba^{2}b
\]

\end_inset

but 
\begin_inset Formula $ba^{2}ba^{2}ba^{2}=e$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $ba^{2}=e\ \implies b=a$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ab^{2}=a^{2}b^{2}\ \implies a=e
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ba^{2}=a^{2}b^{2}\ \implies bab=a
\]

\end_inset

but 
\begin_inset Formula $ababab=e$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $b=e$
\end_inset

.
 We now have 9 distinct elements 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e,a,b,a^{2},b^{2},ab,ab^{2},ba^{2},a^{2}b^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

What is 
\begin_inset Formula $ba$
\end_inset

? It cannot be 
\begin_inset Formula $e,a,b,a^{2},b^{2},ba^{2},ab^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 It cannot be 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}b^{2}$
\end_inset

 because then 
\begin_inset Formula $abab=e$
\end_inset

 which would imply 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=e$
\end_inset

.
 So finally we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $ab=ba$
\end_inset

 and now it is easy to show that the group is abelian.
\end_layout

