\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Remark.

\series default
 It follows from this that if 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a finite group then the number of elements of order 
\begin_inset Formula $d\left(>0\right)$
\end_inset

 is divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\left(d\right)$
\end_inset

.
 For if 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are elements of order 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 then both 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle a\right\rangle $
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle b\right\rangle $
\end_inset

have 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\left(d\right)$
\end_inset

 generators.
 So either the set of generators are disjoint or equal.
 Thus the number of elements which have order 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\left(d\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eulertotient"

\end_inset

For any 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbf{N}$
