\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is unique.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Suppose (iii) holds.
 If there are no elements of order 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, then there is nothing to check.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
If 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is an element of order 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $H=\left\langle g\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of order 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, which has exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\left(d\right)$
\end_inset

 elements of order 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 has atleast 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\left(d\right)$
\end_inset

 elements of order 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
By (iii), 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is the unique subgroup of order 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, if 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{0}$
\end_inset

 is any element of order 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{0}\in H$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 contains exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(d)$
\end_inset

 elements of order 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 has exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(d)$
\end_inset

 elements of order 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Finally assume (iv) holds and suppose that
\begin_inset Formula $\left|G\right|=n$
\end_inset

.
 For any positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{d}$
\end_inset

 be the number of elements of order 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{d}=0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $d\nmid\left|G\right|$
\end_inset

.
 By hypothesis 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{d}\le\varphi\left(d\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore we have by Corollary 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eulertotient"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|G\right|=n=\sum_{d|n}r_{d}\le\sum_{d|n}\varphi(d)=n=\left|G\right|.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So equality must hold, which gives 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{d}=\varphi(d)$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 divisor of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{\ensuremath{\left|G\right|}}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{n}=\varphi(n)\ge1$
\end_inset

.
 So there is an element of order 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|G\right|$
\end_inset

, which means that 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is cyclic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a finite abelian group in which the number of solutions in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 of the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}=e$
\end_inset

 is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 for every positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 must be a cyclic group.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Soln.

\series default
 For any positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{k}$
\end_inset

 be the number of elements of order 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{k}=0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $k\nmid\left|G\right|$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 is of order 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $l,l^{2},\ldots,l^{k}$
\end_inset

 are solutions of 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{k}=e$
\end_inset

.
 Since there are at most 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 solutions, these are all the solutions.
 However, there are only 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(k)$
\end_inset

 among them whose order is 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{k}\le\varphi(k)$
\end_inset

.
 The result follows from Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cyclicequivcond"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a prime.
 A group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n},\, n>1$
\end_inset

 is cyclic if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is an abelian group having a unique subgroup of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
If 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is cyclic of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

 then it is abelian and has a unique subgroup of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 by Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "uniquesubgroupofcyclic"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Suppose now that 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is an abelian group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is prime and 
\begin_inset Formula $n>1$
\end_inset

, and has a unique subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in G$
\end_inset

 have maximal order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{k}$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $0<k<n$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $G\neq\left\langle a\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 By uniqueness 
\begin_inset Formula $H\le\left\langle a\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We will first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists\, x\in G\setminus\left\langle a\right\rangle ,\, x^{p}\in\left\langle a\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 For suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{p}\not\in\left\langle a\right\rangle \,\forall\, x\in G\setminus\left\langle a\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 Then by induction 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{p^{m}}\not\in\left\langle a\right\rangle \,\forall\, m\in\mathbf{N}$
\end_inset

 which leads to a contradiction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
So let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in G\setminus\left\langle a\right\rangle ,\, x^{p}\in\left\langle a\right\rangle .$
\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{p}=a^{l}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e=\left(x^{p}\right)^{p^{k}}=\left(a^{l}\right)^{p^{k}}=a^{lp^{k}}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}\mid lp^{k}$
\end_inset

 by Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "propertiesoforder"

\end_inset

(iv).
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $k<n$
\end_inset

 it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $l=mp$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbf{N}$
\end_inset

 .
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{p}=a^{mp}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x^{-1}a^{m}\right)^{p}=e$
\end_inset

.
 By Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cyclic-2"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-1}a^{m}\in H$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left\langle a\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 which is a contradiction.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $k=n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\left\langle a\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Normal Subgroups and Quotient Groups
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The traditional presentation of normal subgroups and quotient groups goes
 something like this.
 First, you define a subgroup to be normal if it satisfies a certain funny
 condition.
 Then, given a group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and a normal subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, you show that you can define an operation on the cosets of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, and that that operation turns the set of all cosets into a group, called
 the quotient group.
 Ideally, you also show that one can’t give a natural group structure to
 the left cosets of an arbitrary subgroup: that justifies restricting attention
 to normal subgroups.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There’s nothing terribly wrong with this approach, but it does leave one
 question unanswered: why bother with all this stuff? The traditional approach
 to that question is to ignore it, confident that the answer will gradually
 reveal itself.
 The more group theory you do, the more normal subgroups and quotients will
 arise naturally and demonstrate their utility, so if you just diligently
 keep studying, you will (fairly soon) come to regard normal subgroups and
 quotient groups as natural concepts that were obviously worth introducing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But a slight variant of the question is harder to answer: why did anybody
 bother to introduce these concepts in the first place? Surely the concepts
 were introduced for a reason, and not in the vague hope that they would
 turn out to be useful.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The obvious way of answering this second question is to look at the history.
 It turns out that normal subgroups were introduced by Galois (who was also
 the founder of group theory) as part of his study of the solubility of
 polynomials by radicals.
 That’s slightly unfortunate, since it means that to understand why normal
 subgroups were introduced, one has to put in a lot of work understanding
 about the theory of solving polynomials.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, there is another way of justifying the introduction of a new concept
 into mathematics.
 Instead of looking at the actual history of that concept, one can look
 at a 
\emph on
fictitious
\emph default
 history.
 If you can tell a plausible story about why a concept 
\emph on
might
\emph default
 have been invented, then that is sufficient to make it seem reasonable.
 It solves the mystery of how anyone could have thought of the concept,
 and it also shows that it was pretty well inevitable that the concept would
 have been introduced sooner or later.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first phase of group theory (in this fictitious account) consisted in
 spotting that many mathematical structures, such as symmetries of Platonic
 solids, permutations of a finite set, non-singular 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrices, had features in common that could be abstracted out.
 This led to the formulation of the axioms for group theory: associativity,
 identity, inverses.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It was noticed very early---indeed, this observation was part of what drove
 the initial development of the subject---that two groups could be defined
 very differently and yet be ``basically the same''.
 For example, the group of rotations of a regular pentagon was basically
 the same as the group of integers mod 5 under addition, and the group of
 symmetries of a rectangle (that wasn’t a square) was basically the same
 as the group of transformations of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathbf{R}}^{3}$
\end_inset

 that consisted of the identity and the three half turns about the coordinate
 axes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first attempts to make precise this intuition that groups could be ``differe
nt but basically the same'' were a little clumsy.
 Two groups 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 were said to be identical up to permutation and relabelling if you could
 find orderings of the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 such that if you formed the multiplication tables, then they would correspond,
 in the sense that if the element listed in the 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

th place times the element listed in the 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

th place equals the element listed in the 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

th place in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, then the same is true in 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 Later, this definition was tidied up so that it became the definition of
 isomorphism that we are now familiar with: an isomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is a bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\,:\, G\longrightarrow H$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(xy)=\phi(x)\phi(y)$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in G$
\end_inset

.
 Two groups 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 were said to be isomorphic if there was an isomorphism between them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Homomorphisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A further important step was taken when it was observed that functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 that satisfy the multiplicativity property 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(xy)=\phi(x)\phi(y)$
\end_inset

 were interesting and important even if they weren’t bijections.
 To give just one of many examples, an extremely useful property of determinants
 is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(AB)$
\end_inset

 is always equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(A)\det(B)$
\end_inset

.
 Phenomena such as this led people to study what were initially called 
\emph on
multiplicative
\emph default
 functions between groups.
 Later, they were renamed 
\emph on
homomorphisms
\emph default
, to stress the similarity with isomorphisms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\,:\, G\longrightarrow H$
\end_inset

 between two groups is a 
\emph on
homorphism
\emph default
 if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(gh\right)=\phi\left(g\right)\phi\left(h\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Basic properties of homomorphisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "homo"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\,\colon\, G\longrightarrow H$
\end_inset

 be a homomorphism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(i) 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(e\right)=f$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 maps the identity in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 to the identity in 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(a^{-1}\right)=\left(\phi\left(a\right)\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 maps inverses to inverses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(iii) If 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(K\right)$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(iv) If 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{-1}\left(L\right)=\left\{ g\in G\,\colon\:\phi\left(g\right)\in L\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\phi\left(e\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is the identity in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
a & = & \phi\left(e\right)\\
 & = & \phi\left(ee\right)\\
 & = & \phi\left(e\right)\phi\left(e\right)\\
 & = & a^{2}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Cancelling we get 
\begin_inset Formula $a=f$
\end_inset

, the identity in 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 Hence (i).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $b=a^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
f & = & \phi\left(e\right)\\
 & = & \phi\left(ab\right)\\
 & = & \phi\left(a\right)\phi\left(b\right),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
f & = & \phi\left(e\right)\\
 & = & \phi\left(ba\right)\\
 & = & \phi\left(b\right)\phi\left(a\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

But then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(b\right)$
\end_inset

 is the inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(a\right)$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(a^{-1}\right)=\left(\phi\left(a\right)\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence (ii).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\phi\left(K\right)$
\end_inset

.
 It suffices to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is non-empty and closed under products and inverses.
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 the identity of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, by (i).
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is closed under inverses by (ii) and closed under products, by definition
 of homomorphism.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup.
 This proves (iii).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{-1}\left(L\right)$
\end_inset

 is non-empty because 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is non-empty and contains the identity 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 so by (i) 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in\phi^{-1}\left(L\right).$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
If 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\phi^{-1}\left(L\right)$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(a\right),\phi\left(b\right)\in L.$
\end_inset

 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(a\right)\phi\left(b\right)=\phi\left(ab\right)\in L.$
\end_inset

 i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\in\phi^{-1}\left(L\right).$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Finally 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\phi^{-1}\left(L\right)$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(a\right)$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\phi\left(a\right)\right)^{-1}=\phi\left(a^{-1}\right)\in L$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{-1}\in\phi^{-1}\left(L\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This proves (iv).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
