, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\textrm{ker }\phi}=\left\{ e\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Now suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\textrm{ker }\phi}=\left\{ e\right\} $
\end_inset

 and suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(x\right)=\phi\left(y\right).$
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g=x^{-1}y.$
\end_inset

 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\phi\left(g\right) & = & \phi\left(x^{-1}y\right)\\
 & = & \phi\left(x\right)^{-1}\phi\left(y\right)\\
 & = & f.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Thus g is in the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $g=e$
\end_inset

.
 But then 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-1}y=e$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is injective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By this time, people had got a bit of a taste for the purely abstract study
 of group theory: it excited them that they could think about a group such
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{5}$
\end_inset

 without saying whether its elements were rotations of a pentagon or integers
 mod 5 or something else entirely.
 So people started studying groups 
\emph on
for their own sake
\emph default
.
 And one of the first questions they asked was this: we know that kernels
 of homomorphisms are subgroups, but what about the converse? That is, is
 every subgroup the kernel of some homomorphism?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This problem turned out not to be very interesting, since there were easy
 counterexamples.
 For example, if you take the permutation group 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{3}$
\end_inset

 and take the subgroup that consists of the identity and the transposition
 
\begin_inset Formula $(12)$
\end_inset

, then that is not the kernel of any homomorphism.
 The original proof of this fact went something like this.
 Suppose we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $(12)$
\end_inset

 goes to the identity.
 We can use that to deduce that, say, 
\begin_inset Formula $(23)$
\end_inset

 also goes to the identity.
 We do this by ``using 
\begin_inset Formula $(12)$
\end_inset

 to do 
\begin_inset Formula $(23)$
\end_inset

'' as follows.
 We first find a permutation that switches 1 and 3---the obvious one being
 
\begin_inset Formula $(13)$
\end_inset

.
 We then switch 1 and 3, perform the permutation 
\begin_inset Formula $(12)$
\end_inset

 and finally switch 1 and 3 back again.
 More formally, we calculate the permutation 
\begin_inset Formula $(13)(12)(13)$
\end_inset

, and we note that because we began and ended by swapping 1 and 3 round,
 this new permutation does to 3 what the old one did to 1 and vice versa.
 So the resulting permutation is 
\begin_inset Formula $(32)$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $(12)$
\end_inset

---and 
\begin_inset Formula $(32)$
\end_inset

 is the same as 
\begin_inset Formula $(23)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What does that prove? Well, if we now think about what 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(23)$
\end_inset

 must be, it is the result of multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(13)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(12)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(13)$
\end_inset

.
 But since 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(12)$
\end_inset

 is the identity and 
\begin_inset Formula $(13)$
\end_inset

 is its own inverse, we end up just doing 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(13)$
\end_inset

 and inverting it again.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $(23)$
\end_inset

 also belongs to the kernel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It was soon realized that this basic trick could be used to generate lots
 of counterexamples.
 All you had to do was find a group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, a subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, an element 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

 and an element 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ghg^{-1}$
\end_inset

 was not in 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 And that was easy to do.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Soon this observation was turned into a formal definition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Normal Subgroups.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "normal"

\end_inset

A subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 of a group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\emph on
closed under conjugation 
\emph default
or 
\emph on
normal 
\emph default
and write 
\begin_inset Formula $H\vartriangleleft G,$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $ghg^{-1}\in H$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the normality condition can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $gHg^{-1}\subseteq H$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group and 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 a subgroup.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is the only subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 of some given order 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is normal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Soln.
 
\begin_inset Formula $gHg^{-1}$
\end_inset


\series default
 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 with the same order 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 hence 
\begin_inset Formula $gHg^{-1}=H.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now the original question was modified in an obvious way.
 The argument used to generate counterexamples could be encapsulated in
 the following statement: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "kernelhomo"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\colon G\longrightarrow H$
\end_inset

 be a group homomorphism.
 Then the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is a normal subgroup of G.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We have already seen that the kernel is a subgroup.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
 We want to prove that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g\,\mathrm{\textrm{ker }\phi\,}g^{-1}\subset\mathrm{\textrm{ker }\phi}.
\]

\end_inset

Suppose that
\begin_inset Formula $h\in\mathrm{\textrm{ker }\phi.}$
\end_inset

 We need to prove that 
