\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "abeliannormal"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be an abelian group and let 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 be any subgroup.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
For every 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ghg^{-1}=gg^{-1}h=h\in H.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prodNH"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group, 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 a normal subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 be any subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(i) 
\begin_inset Formula $HN=NH.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $HN$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(iii) 
\begin_inset Formula $N\vartriangleleft HN.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
(i) Since 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is normal,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
HN=\left\{ hN\,\colon\, h\in H\right\} =\left\{ Nh\,\colon\, h\in H\right\} =NH.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
(ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $HN$
\end_inset

 is non-empty because it contains the identity.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{1}n_{1},h_{2}n_{2}\in HN.$
\end_inset

 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
h_{1}n_{1}h_{2}n_{2} & = & h_{1}\left(n_{1}h_{2}\right)n_{2}=h_{1}h_{3}n_{3}n_{2}\in HN,\\
\left(h_{1}n_{1}\right)^{-1} & =n_{1}^{-1}h_{1}^{-1} & =hn\in HN.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
(iii) Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $HN$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $gN=Ng$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $N\vartriangleleft HN.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "normalequivdef"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 be a subgroup of a group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Then the following statements are equivalent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(i) 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(ii) For every 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $gHg^{-1}=H.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(iii) 
\begin_inset Formula $Hg=gH$
\end_inset

, for every 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Clearly (ii) and (iii) are equivalent and (ii) implies (i) since 
\begin_inset Formula $gHg^{-1}\subseteq H.$
\end_inset

 Thus it remains to show that (i) implies (ii).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Suppose that (i) holds.
 Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
gHg^{-1}\subseteq H.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Now replace 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g^{-1}Hg\subseteq H,
\]

\end_inset

so that multiplying on the left by 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and the right by 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H\subseteq gHg^{-1}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Thus (ii) holds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So what about the converse? Is every subgroup that is closed under conjugation
 the kernel of some homomorphism?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This question is an example of a phenomenon that occurs frequently in mathematic
s.
 You find a very simple 
\emph on
necessary
\emph default
 condition for something to be the case.
 (In this example, being closed under conjugation is a necessary condition
 for a subgroup to be the kernel of a homomorphism.) You then attempt to
 show that that condition is 
\emph on
sufficient
\emph default
.
 It’s always a pleasant surprise when you manage, since it is far from obvious
 in advance that the conditions you have identified are the only obstacles
 to getting what you want.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, for instance, it isn’t obvious at all that just because a subgroup
 satisfies a condition that it clearly has to satisfy, it must be the kernel
 of some homomorphism.
 Where’s that homomorphism going to come from? There isn’t another group
 around, let alone a map from 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 to that group.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This problem was found quite hard at the time, though the technique used
 to solve it has since become standard.
 The original thought process that led to a solution went something like
 this.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
If you are trying to find something complicated but have no idea where to
 start, then pretend you’ve found what you are looking for and see what
 you can say about it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Cosets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So let’s pretend we have a homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 to some group 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and that the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 What can we say about 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Well, one thing we know immediately is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(h)=e$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

, since that was our initial assumption.
 What can we do with that information? One thing it tells us is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(g)=\phi(gh)$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

, and also that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(g)=\phi(hg)$
\end_inset

.
 So that tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(g)=\phi(g')$
\end_inset

 whenever we can find 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g'=hg$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $g'=gh$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let’s explore that a little more.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 be an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Can we say precisely for which elements 
\begin_inset Formula $g'\in G$
\end_inset

 it must be the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(g)=\phi(g')$
\end_inset

? We’ve shown that it must when 
\begin_inset Formula $g'=hg$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $gh$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

.
 To prove that, we used the fact that every 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

 belongs to the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 But we also know the converse: that every element of the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 belongs to 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 So if 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(g)=\phi(g')$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}g'\in H$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(g^{-1}g')=\phi(g^{-1})\phi(g')=\phi(g)^{-1}\phi(g)=e$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What we have just established, using only the information that 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(g)=\phi(g')$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}g'\in H$
\end_inset

, which is the same as saying that 
\begin_inset Formula $g'\in gH$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where have we got to now? We have shown that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is a homomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 to a group 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, and if the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 must be constant on the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $gH.$
\end_inset

 Also, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 must take a different value on 
\begin_inset Formula $g'H$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $gH\neq g'H.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But I could have argued slightly differently.
 I could have shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(g)=\phi(g')$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(g'g^{-1})=e$
\end_inset

, and therefore concluded that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(g)=\phi(g')$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $g'g^{-1}\in H$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $g'\in Hg$
\end_inset

.
 This would have shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is constant on 
\begin_inset Formula $Hg$
\end_inset

, and that it takes a different value on 
\begin_inset Formula $Hg'$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $Hg\neq Hg'$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These two observations are incompatible with each other unless 
\begin_inset Formula $gH=Hg'$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $g'\in G.$
\end_inset

 and vice versa.
 So we’d better check that.
 What is a good choice for 
\begin_inset Formula $g'$
\end_inset

? Well, 
\begin_inset Formula $Hg'$
\end_inset

 had better contain 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $Hg$
\end_inset

 is a pretty obvious choice.
 Does 
\begin_inset Formula $gH=Hg$
\end_inset

? The answer is yes if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $gHg^{-1}=H$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is closed under conjugation, so by Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "normalequivdef"

\end_inset

(ii) we’re OK.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We state the above results as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "homoconstcosets"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 be a homomorphism from a group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 to some group 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and that the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is constant on 
\begin_inset Formula $gH$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in H$
\end_inset

 but takes a different value on 
\begin_inset Formula $g'H$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $gH\neq g'H$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover 
\begin_inset Formula $gH=Hg$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Note*
The above discussion also shows that the collection of sets 
\begin_inset Formula $gH$
\end_inset

 form a disjoint partition of 
\begin_inset Formula $G.$
\end_inset

 This should suggest some equivalence relation lurking around.
 We shall return to this later.
 For the time being let us use the standard terminology 
\emph on
left coset
\emph default
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $gH$
\end_inset

 and 
\emph on
right coset
\emph default
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $Hg.$
\end_inset

 In the present case since left and right cosets coincide we just call them
 cosets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is that all we can say? Very much not.
 If we have an ounce of mathematical curiosity, then sooner or later we
 will start to wonder whether we can say anything about how the values of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 on different cosets are related to each other.
 If we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 takes the value 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 everywhere on the coset 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}H$
\end_inset

 and the value 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 everywhere on the coset 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}H$
\end_inset

, can we deduce anything from that? Well, the main thing we know about 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is that it is a homomorphism, so let’s try to use that fact.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{1},h_{2}\in H$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(g_{1}h_{1})=a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(g_{2}h_{2})=b$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(g_{1}h_{1}g_{2}h_{2})=ab$
\end_inset

, by the multiplicativity property.
 By what we have just established, that tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 will take the value 
\begin_inset Formula $ab$
\end_inset

 on the entire coset to which 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}h_{1}g_{2}h_{2}$
\end_inset

 belongs.
 But what is that coset? To answer that we would like to rewrite 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}h_{1}g_{2}h_{2}$
\end_inset

 as a product that begins with something in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and ends with something in 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 It would be nice if we could let 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 swap places.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Can we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{1}g_{2}=g_{2}h_{1}$
\end_inset

? Unfortunately not.
 But let’s play around a little.
 We know that 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is closed under conjugation, so we might try to find a conjugation.
 And we can! Rearranging the equation we were hoping for gives us that 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}^{-1}h_{1}g_{2}=h_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 There is no reason to suppose that that is true, but we do at least know
 that the left hand side belongs to 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 So we can at least write 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}^{-1}h_{1}g_{2}=h_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 And rearranging that tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}h_{3}=h_{1}g_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}h_{1}g_{2}h_{2}=g_{1}g_{2}h_{3}h_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 That tells us that the coset that contains 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}h_{1}g_{2}h_{2}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}g_{2}H$
\end_inset

, which is as nice an answer as we could have hoped for.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What does this tell us? Let’s write 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(gH)=a$
\end_inset

 to mean that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 takes the value 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 everywhere on the coset 
\begin_inset Formula $gH$
\end_inset

