\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "generatorsofA_n"

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq3$
\end_inset

 the alternating group 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}$
\end_inset

 is generated by the set of all 3-cycles in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
3-cycles are even permutations by Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "parityofk-cycle"

\end_inset

, so they all lie in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 By definition every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}$
\end_inset

 is a product of an even number of 2-cycles, so it suffices to show that
 every product 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(i,j\right)\left(k,l\right)$
\end_inset

 is a product of 3-cycles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Using eqn.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:productoftranspositions"

\end_inset

 we can write for a 3-cycle
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(i,j,k\right)=\left(j,k,i\right)=\left(j,i\right)\left(j,k\right)=\left(i,j\right)\left(j,k\right)\label{eq:3cycledecomposition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If the two cycles 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(i,j\right),\left(k,l\right)$
\end_inset

 are equal their product is identity 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(1,2,3\right)\left(1,3,2\right)=e.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
If 
\begin_inset Formula $j=k$
\end_inset

 then by eqn.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:3cycledecomposition"

\end_inset

we get the result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
If all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j,k,l$
\end_inset

 are distinct the again by eqn.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:3cycledecomposition"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(i,j,k\right)\left(j,k,l\right)=\left(i,j\right)\left(j,k\right)\left(j,k\right)\left(k,l\right)=\left(i,j\right),\left(k,l\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

