\begin_layout Section
Equivalence Relations and Counting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this chapter we shall exploit a simple but very profound idea from set
 theory viz., that of an equivalence relation.
 We shall derive some very important results in group theory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Fact 1.

\series default
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be any finite set and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

be an equivalence relation.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1},A_{2},\ldots,A_{n}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 distinct equivalence classes of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

so that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X=\bigcup_{i=i}^{n}A_{i}
\]

\end_inset

then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|X\right|={\displaystyle \sum_{i=1}^{n}\left|A_{i}\right|}.
\]

\end_inset

In particular if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|A_{i}\right|=m$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|X\right|=m\cdot n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus an equivalence relation can be used to count the elements of a set
 or if the count is known then it allows us to determine the number of equivalen
ce classes if each class has the same number of elements.
 In the latter case 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 must be a divisor of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|X\right|$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The counting result above is very useful.
 For it gives us the possible cardinality of the subgroups of any finite
 group.
 This is the content of the celebrated 
\emph on
Lagrange's Theorem
\emph default
 one of the most important theorems in Group Theory.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Fact 2.

\series default
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\,\colon\, X\longrightarrow Y$
\end_inset

 be any map.
 We can partition 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by an equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 by declaring 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=f\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Then the map 
\begin_inset Formula $F\,\colon\, X/\sim\longrightarrow Y$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F\left(\left[x\right]\right)=f\left(x\right)
\]

\end_inset

is well defined and injective.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is surjective then 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a bijection.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{card }X/\sim\leq\mbox{card }Y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Definitions and properties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
During the discussion leading to Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "homoconstcosets"

\end_inset

 we alluded to the fact that the cosets 
\begin_inset Formula $gH$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is the kernel of some homomphism of a group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 effect a partition of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 This partition must correspond to a unique equivalence relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $G.$
\end_inset

 This notion is a very general one and valid for any subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 not necessarily normal.
 In fact it will be useful in some cases when 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is not a subgroup.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "coset"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group, let 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 be a subgroup and let 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G.$
\end_inset

 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
gH=\left\{ gh\,\colon\, h\in H\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

is called a 
\emph on
left coset
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $G.$
\end_inset

 Similarly 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Hg=\left\{ hg\,\colon\, h\in H\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

is called a 
\emph on
right coset
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $G.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "cardofcoset"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group, let 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 be a subgroup and let 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G.$
\end_inset

 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|gH\right|=\left|H\right|=\left|Hg\right|
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Fix any 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $gH$
\end_inset

 is a left coset of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Define a map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\,\colon\, H\longrightarrow gH,
\]

\end_inset

by sending 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $A(h)=gh$
\end_inset

.
 Define a map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B\,\colon\, gH\longrightarrow H,
\]

\end_inset

by sending 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in gH$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $B(k)=g^{-1}k$
\end_inset

.
 These maps are both clearly well-defined.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We show that 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 We first compute
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B\circ A\,\colon\, H\longrightarrow H.
\]

\end_inset

Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left(B\circ A\right)\left(h\right) & = & B\left(A\left(h\right)\right)\\
 & = & B\left(gh\right)\\
 & = & g^{-1}\left(gh\right)\\
 & = & h.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Now consider
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\circ B\colon\, gH\longrightarrow gH.
\]

\end_inset

Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in gH$
\end_inset

 , then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left(A\circ B\right)\left(k\right) & = & A\left(B\left(k\right)\right)\\
 & = & A\left(g^{-1}k\right)\\
 & = & g\left(g^{-1}k\right)\\
 & = & k.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 must be a bijection and so 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $gH$
\end_inset

 must have the same cardinality.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Hg$
\end_inset

 have the same cardinality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "cosetpartition"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 be a subgroup of a group 
\begin_inset Formula $G.$
\end_inset

 The set of left (or right) cosets effect a partition of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 which corresponds to the equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim b$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{-1}a\in H$
\end_inset

 (resp.
 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim b$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $ab^{-1}\in H$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in gH$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in H.$
\end_inset

 Therefore,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G={\displaystyle \bigcup_{g\in G}gH.}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We will next show that any two left cosets are either disjoint or equal.
 Let us suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left(aH\right)\cap\left(bH\right).$
\end_inset

 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x=ah_{1}=bh_{2}$
\end_inset

 for suitable 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{1},h_{2}\in H$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $a=bh_{2}h_{1}^{-1}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $aH\subseteq bH.$
\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g=ah\in aH.$
\end_inset

 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $g=bh_{2}h_{1}^{-1}h\in H.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $bH\subseteq aH.$
\end_inset

 Thus the cosets 
\begin_inset Formula $aH$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $bH$
\end_inset

 are equal.
 This proves that the set of left cosets effect a partition of 
\begin_inset Formula $G.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Suppose now that 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in gH.$
\end_inset

 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $a=gh_{1},b=gh_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{-1}a=h_{2}^{-1}h_{1}\in H.$
\end_inset

 Conversely 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{-1}a\in H$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in bH$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim b$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{-1}a\in H.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

