\begin_inset Formula $\left[G\,:\, K\right]=m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[K\,:\, H\right]=n$
\end_inset

 are finite.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}K,\ldots,g_{m}K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}H,\ldots,k_{n}H$
\end_inset

 be the distinct right coset representatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 We will show that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ g_{i}k_{j}H\,\colon\,1\leq i\leq m,\,1\leq j\leq n\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

are the distinct right cosets of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}k_{j}H=g_{r}k_{s}H$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{s}^{-1}g_{r}^{-1}g_{i}k_{j}\in H\subseteq K$
\end_inset

 hence 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{r}^{-1}g_{i}\in K$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}=g_{r}.$
\end_inset

 The equality 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}k_{j}H=g_{r}k_{s}H$
\end_inset

 then shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{j}=k_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Now
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\displaystyle \bigcup_{i=1}^{m}\bigcup_{j=1}^{n}g_{i}k_{j}H=\bigcup_{i=1}^{m}g_{i}K=G.}
\]

\end_inset

The argument above shows that if either 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is infinite the there are an infinite number of right cosets of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 so in all cases we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[G\,:\, H\right]=\left[G\,:\, K\right]\cdot\left[K\,:\, H\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

