\begin_layout Standard
In Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "abeliannormal"

\end_inset

 we saw that an abelian group is normal.
 It is easy to find examples to show that the converse is not true.
 For example take 
\begin_inset Formula $G=D_{3}$
\end_inset

 the group of symmetries of an equilateral triangle.
 This group consists of the identity 
\begin_inset Formula $I,R$
\end_inset

 a rotation through 
\begin_inset Formula $60^{\circ}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 together with three flips which are reflections in the medians.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H=\left\{ I,R,R^{2}\right\} .$
\end_inset

 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $G.$
\end_inset

 To verify this first suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in H.$
\end_inset

 Then clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $ghg^{-1}\in H$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H.$
\end_inset

 Otherwise 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is a flip.
 Let us suppose that it is 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Now pick 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

 and consider 
\begin_inset Formula $ghg^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $h=I$
\end_inset

 then it is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $ghg^{-1}=I\in H$
\end_inset

.
 So suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $h=R$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
ghg^{-1} & = & F_{1}RF_{1}\\
 & = & R^{2}\in H.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Similarly, if 
\begin_inset Formula $h=R^{2}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $ghg^{-1}=R\in H$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Now suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $h=F_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g=R$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
ghg^{-1} & = & RF_{1}R\\
 & = & F_{2}\not\neq F_{1}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is not abelian.
 The notion of conjugation measures how far the group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is from being abelian.
\end_layout

