\begin_inset Formula $ghg^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\emph on
conjugate
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is abelian iff the conjugate of every element by any other element is the
 same element.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group.
 We say that two elements 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are 
\emph on
conjugate
\emph default
, if there is a third element 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b=gag^{-1}
\]

\end_inset

and write 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim b$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are conjugate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "conjeqrel"

\end_inset

The relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 of being conjugate is an equivalence relation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We have to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is reflexive, symmetrmic and transitive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in G$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $eae^{-1}=a$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim a$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is reflexive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in G$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim b$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is conjugate to 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 By definition this means that there is an element 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $gag^{-1}=b$
\end_inset

.
 But then 
\begin_inset Formula $a=g^{-1}bg=hbh^{-1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $h=g^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $b\sim a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is symmetric.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Finally suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\sim c$
\end_inset

.
 Then there are elements 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $b=gag^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c=hbh^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
c & = & hbh^{-1}\\
 & = & hgag^{-1}h^{-1}\\
 & = & \left(hg\right)a\left(hg\right)^{-1}=kak^{-1},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k=hg.$
\end_inset

 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is transitive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is an equivalence relation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "conjugacyclass"

\end_inset

The equivalence classes of the equivalence relation above are called a 
\emph on
conjugacy classes
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{x}$
\end_inset

 be the conjugacy class containing the element 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 .
