\begin_layout Standard
We have seen (Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "normalequivdef-2"

\end_inset

) that normal subgroups are unions of conjugacy classes.
 So conjugacy classes are used to construct normal subgroups.
 Normal subgroups are used to study groups 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 by looking at the simpler quotient groups 
\begin_inset Formula $G/N$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 needs to be a normal subgroup.
 A group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\emph on
simple 
\emph default
if it has no proper non-trivial normal subgroups.
 One can prove the simplicity of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}$
\end_inset

 using the concept of centralizer and conjugacy class.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The class equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:classeqn"

\end_inset

 leads quickly to a proof of Sylow's Theorem.
 Conjugacy classes and centralizers are related to a certain type of group
 action, a group acting on itself by conjugation.
 This action gives us a lot of information about the group.
 The conjugacy classes fit into this picture as the orbits of elements of
 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 under this action, while the centralizers are their stabilizers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once you get used to how group actions work, it becomes much easier to see
 the importance of conjugacy classes and centralizers.
 For an elementary example, you can tell that 
\begin_inset Formula $|\mathfrak{\mathscr{O}}_{x}|=\left[G\,\colon\, C_{G}(x)\right]$
\end_inset

 (Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cardconjclass"

\end_inset

) for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 It's good to know how many elements a given element is conjugate to, and
 it's very interesting that this number must divide the order of the group.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a less elementary example, we can look at how groups act on other sets.
 A 
\emph on
representation 
\emph default
of a group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $G\longrightarrow\mathbf{GL}(V)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is a vector space.
 Usually we are most interested in representations into 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{GL_{n}}(C)$
\end_inset

.
 A character is what we call the 
\emph on
trace
\emph default
 of a representation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Characters are not necessarily homomorphisms, but, as it turns out, they
 are 
\emph on
class functions
\emph default
, meaning that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 is a character, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi(x)=\chi(y)$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are in the same conjugacy class of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 So, if we know all the conjugacy classes of the group, we can much more
 easily compute the characters of the group's representations (and tell
 a lot of other things about them too).
 You can see why it would be useful to do this, as symmetries of vector
 spaces are essential to mathematics in general.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another important fact, proved using group characters, is Burnside's Theorem
 that in a finite non-Abelian simple group no non-identity element can lie
 in a conjugacy class whose size is a power of a prime.
 This leads quickly to Burnside's Theorem that a finite group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{a}q^{b}$
\end_inset

 is solvable when 
\begin_inset Formula $p,q$
\end_inset

 are primes, and 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 are positive integers.
 There are many other uses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In both infinite and finite groups, the notion of conjugacy is useful in
 exhibiting structure.
 For example, the decomposition of permutations as products of disjoint
 cycles makes the relation of conjugacy especially transparent in the symmetric
 group.
 The notion of Jordan normal form makes the conjugacy classes in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{GL}(n,F)$
\end_inset

 transparent when 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is an algebraically closed field.
 The notion of rational canonical form makes the conjugacy classes in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{GL}(n,F)$
\end_inset

 transparent when 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a not necessarily algebraically closed field (Jordan normal form is
 really a special case of the latter) .
\end_layout

