\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "cycledecompositionofconjugate"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma,\tau$
\end_inset

 be two elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma=\left(a_{1},a_{2},\ldots,a_{k}\right)\left(b_{1},b_{2},\ldots,b_{l}\right)\ldots
\]

\end_inset

is the cycle decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tau\sigma\tau^{-1}=\left(\tau\left(a_{1}\right),\tau\left(a_{2}\right),\ldots,\tau\left(a_{k}\right)\right)\left(\tau\left(b_{1}\right),\tau\left(b_{2}\right),\ldots,\tau\left(b_{l}\right)\right)\ldots\label{eq:cycledecompositionofconjugate}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is the cycle decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\sigma\tau^{-1}$
\end_inset

, the conjugate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Since both sides of the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:cycledecompositionofconjugate"

\end_inset

 are permutations, it suffices to check that both sides have the same effect
 on any integer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is surjective, 
\begin_inset Formula $j=\tau(i)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 We may as well assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $j=\tau(a_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 This is because disjoint cycles commute and within each cycle we can rotate
 the elements.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(a_{1})=a_{2}$
\end_inset

 and the right hand side of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:cycledecompositionofconjugate"

\end_inset

 maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(a_{1})$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $τ(a\mbox{2})$
\end_inset

.
 But
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left(\tau\sigma\tau^{-1}\right)\left(\tau\left(a_{1}\right)\right) & = & \tau\sigma\left(a_{1}\right)\\
 & = & \tau\left(a_{2}\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Thus the LHS and RHS of eqn.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:cycledecompositionofconjugate"

\end_inset

 have the same effect on 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and so they must be equal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In other words, to compute the conjugate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, just translate the elements of the cycle decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 For example suppose
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma=\left(3,7,4,2\right)\left(1,6,5\right)
\]

\end_inset

in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{8}$
\end_inset

 i.e.,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 2 & 3 & 4 & 5 & 6 & 7 & 8\\
6 & 3 & 7 & 2 & 1 & 5 & 4 & 8
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 2 & 3 & 4 & 5 & 6 & 7 & 8\\
3 & 2 & 5 & 1 & 8 & 7 & 6 & 4
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Then the conjugate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\tau\sigma\tau^{-1} & = & \left(\tau\left(3\right),\tau\left(7\right),\tau\left(4\right),\tau\left(2\right)\right)\left(\tau\left(1\right),\tau\left(6\right),\tau\left(5\right)\right)\\
 & = & \left(5,6,1,2\right)\left(3,7,8\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

