\begin_layout Section
Cauchy's Theorem for abelian groups
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cauchy's Theorem is a partial converse to Lagrange's Theorem (that the order
 of any subgroup divides the order of the group).
 We seeks theorems of this kind because it means we can get information
 about the elements of a group just from knowing it's order, and then we
 can start to classify groups.
 i.e.
 we can then say that if a group has a certain size, it will be of a certain
 form.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Theorems like this one (and also the Sylow theorems) aren't obvious, but
 they are very, very useful.
 The proof given below is something that seems totally unnatural (although
 once understood it is very pretty, not to mention clever!) In fact, I don't
 think that there is a core idea behind the proof to be help understand
 why it's true.
 It is just an exercise in clever manipulation, not giving us much insight
 into the problem, in the same way that inductive proofs often give us answers
 but may not help us understand the question better.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "cauchyabelian"

\end_inset

Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is abelian and the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mid n$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 has an element of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},g_{2},\ldots,g_{n}$
\end_inset

 be the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, and for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 be the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Consider the direct sum
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H=\bigoplus_{i=1}^{n}\mathbb{Z}/a_{i}\mathbb{Z}.
\]

\end_inset

 The order of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is obviously 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}a_{2}\cdots\, a_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We can define a group homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x_{1},\ldots,x_{n})\mapsto g_{1}^{x_{1}}\cdots g_{n}^{x_{n}}.
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is certainly surjective.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $|H|=|G|\cdot|\ker(\theta)|$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a prime factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|H\right|$
\end_inset

, and therefore must divide one of the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

's,.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}^{a_{i}/p}$
\end_inset

 is an element of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 by Corollary 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "elementoforderprime"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Remark.

\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is a manufactured group, which is constructed specially for the purpose
 of the proof.
 It is built up using known groups, one for each element of the unknown
 finite group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 The existence of a homomorphism from the known group 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 to the unknown group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 enables us to discover information about 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 using what we know about 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a proof strategy replicated many times, and very useful to know.
\end_layout

